  "signature": "ed25519:b4e9d3c2f5a8017g6b3d9e4c2f5a8017g6b3d9e4c2f5a8017g6b3d9e4c2f5a8",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-level3-criteria",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (OpenFOAM v9) is subject to a documented software quality assurance plan compliant with FDA software guidance. Version control is enforced via Git with tagged releases; all simulation scripts are archived under configuration management. Automated regression test suite covers 47 benchmark cases including rotating machinery and non-Newtonian flow. Code review records and issue tracking logs are available and traceable to simulation outputs. SQA level achieved (4) exceeds the required level (3) for MRL 5 hemolysis prediction, providing additional confidence in solver integrity."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/code-verification-level3-criteria",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification was performed using the method of manufactured solutions (MMS) for the incompressible Navier-Stokes equations with the SST k-omega turbulence closure. Observed order of accuracy (p=1.97) matches theoretical second-order accuracy of the finite-volume discretization to within 2%. Additional verification against analytical Stokes flow solutions and rotating Couette flow confirms correct implementation of the rotating reference frame formulation. All verification cases are archived with input files and output logs. Achieved level (4) exceeds required level (3)."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/discretization-error-level3-criteria",
      "rationale": "Discretization error was quantified using the Grid Convergence Index (GCI) methodology per Celik et al. (2008). Three systematically refined meshes were constructed with refinement ratio r=2 (2.1M, 8.4M, 33.6M hexahedral cells). The GCI for the primary hemolysis QoI is 1.8% on the fine mesh, well below the 3% acceptance threshold. The asymptotic convergence ratio of 0.97 confirms operation in the asymptotic range. Temporal discretization error was assessed separately using three time-step refinements; the fine time-step GCI for hemolysis is 0.6%. Both spatial and temporal discretization errors are documented in the validation report."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-level3-criteria",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions for the validation dataset are fully documented, including fluid properties (bovine blood analog, measured viscosity and density), pump geometry (FDA generic centrifugal pump, dimensional tolerances documented), operating conditions (flow rates 2.5-7.5 L/min, speeds 2500-3500 RPM), and environmental conditions (temperature 37 C, controlled to within 0.5 C). Measurement uncertainty for all test inputs has been quantified and propagated. The achieved level (3) meets the required level (3), confirming adequate characterization of test conditions for this COU."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-level3-criteria",
      "rationale": "Output comparison was performed using both graphical and quantitative metrics. For hemolysis, the mean absolute error (MAE) of 0.0031 g/100L is within the pre-specified acceptance band of 0.005 g/100L across all 5 operating points. For velocity fields, the area-weighted RMS error is 4.2% of the reference velocity scale. The validation metric (E) is compared against the combined experimental and numerical uncertainty (U_val) using the ASME V&V 20 validation metric framework; |E| < U_val for all QoIs. Systematic bias analysis confirms no statistically significant directional error. Achieved level (4) exceeds required level (3)."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-level3-criteria",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI — normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) — is directly clinically relevant and is the regulatory-accepted metric for hemolysis quantification per ASTM F1841. The CFD-predicted hemolysis index is derived from the power-law Giersiepen-Wurzinger model applied to Lagrangian particle tracking, which directly maps to the in-vitro measurement protocol. Secondary QoIs (velocity magnitude, turbulent shear stress) are mechanistically linked to hemolysis through the damage model. The relevance chain from QoI to clinical endpoint is documented in the model development report. Achieved level (4) exceeds required level (3)."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-level3-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation activities were conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is the same geometric archetype as the COU device. Operating conditions in the validation dataset span the full COU operating envelope (flow rate 2.5-7.5 L/min, speed 2500-3500 RPM). The blood analog fluid (glycerol-water mixture calibrated to match bovine blood viscosity) approximates in-vivo conditions to the extent feasible in bench testing. The validation hierarchy includes component-level and system-level validation activities. Achieved level (3) meets required level (3); the remaining gap between bench and in-vivo conditions is acknowledged and bounded by the UQ analysis."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-level3-criteria",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error was assessed through iterative convergence monitoring, round-off error analysis, and solver residual tracking. All simulations were run to residual convergence of 1e-6 for all transported quantities. Mass imbalance across the domain is less than 0.01% of inlet mass flow rate. Floating-point round-off error was assessed using double-precision arithmetic throughout; sensitivity to single vs. double precision was tested on a representative case with negligible difference (0.03% in hemolysis QoI). Solver error contribution to total numerical uncertainty is estimated at less than 0.2% and is formally included in the UQ budget. Achieved level (4) exceeds required level (3)."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-level2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Use error was assessed through a structured review of simulation setup procedures, boundary condition specification, and post-processing workflows. A documented simulation execution protocol (SEP) was followed by all analysts; independent peer review of boundary condition inputs and mesh quality metrics was performed by a second qualified engineer. Pre-defined checklists for mesh quality, boundary condition completeness, and post-processing reproducibility were completed and archived for all production runs. No use errors were identified during the review. The SEP and review records are traceable to the simulation outputs via the provenance chain. Achieved level (3) exceeds required level (2)."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-level3-criteria",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty was assessed through comparison of three turbulence closure models (SST k-omega, realizable k-epsilon, and RSM) and two hemolysis damage models (Giersiepen-Wurzinger power law and Arora mechanistic model). The SST k-omega model with Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis was selected as the primary model based on best agreement with experimental data across the validation dataset. Model form uncertainty (spread across turbulence models) is 12% of predicted hemolysis and is included as an epistemic uncertainty contribution in the Monte Carlo UQ. The model selection rationale is documented and peer-reviewed. Achieved level (3) meets required level (3)."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-level3-criteria",
      "rationale": "All model input parameters are documented with sources, nominal values, and uncertainty bounds. Key inputs include blood viscosity (measured, CV=3.2%), blood density (literature, CV=0.5%), inlet flow rate (measured, CV=1.8%), rotational speed (controlled, CV=0.4%), and hemolysis model coefficients (literature with documented uncertainty ranges). Sobol sensitivity analysis from the Monte Carlo UQ identifies rotational speed and viscosity as the dominant uncertainty sources, accounting for 71% of output variance. Input uncertainty bounds are physically justified and traceable to measurement records or published literature. Achieved level (4) exceeds required level (3)."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-samples-level3-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted on three independently manufactured FDA generic centrifugal pump specimens to assess manufacturing variability. Each specimen was tested at all 5 operating points with three repeat measurements per point, yielding 45 independent experimental observations for hemolysis and 135 for velocity fields. Inter-specimen variability (CV=4.1%) and intra-specimen repeatability (CV=1.8%) are both quantified and included in the experimental uncertainty budget. Sample provenance, storage conditions, and preparation protocols are documented. The sample size is sufficient to estimate population statistics at the required confidence level for MRL 5. Achieved level (3) meets required level (3)."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/input-equivalency-level3-criteria",
      "rationale": "Equivalency between validation experiment input parameters and COU input parameters was assessed using a structured parameter comparison matrix. Fluid properties (viscosity, density, non-Newtonian behavior) are matched to within documented tolerances using the calibrated blood analog. Geometric equivalency is confirmed: the validation pump is the same FDA generic geometry as the COU device. Operating condition equivalency is demonstrated across the full COU envelope. Remaining differences (in-vitro vs. in-vivo blood rheology, absence of pulsatile inlet in validation) are identified, bounded, and included as epistemic uncertainty contributions in the UQ analysis. Achieved level (3) meets required level (3)."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou1-nc1-decision",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 V&V 40 credibility factors have been fully assessed. For each factor, the achieved credibility level meets or exceeds the required level as determined by the Model Risk Level and COU characteristics. Specifically: Software quality assurance (4 >= 3), Numerical code verification (4 >= 3), Discretization error (4 >= 3), Test conditions (3 >= 3), Output comparison (4 >= 3), Relevance of QoI (4 >= 3), Relevance of validation activities (3 >= 3), Numerical solver error (4 >= 3), Use error (3 >= 2), Model form (3 >= 3), Model inputs (4 >= 3), Test samples (3 >= 3), and Equivalency of input parameters (3 >= 3). Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification has been performed with 1000 samples, demonstrating that the 95th-percentile hemolysis prediction remains 18% below the clinical acceptance threshold. The validation dataset spans the full COU operating envelope with three independently manufactured specimens and three repeat measurements per operating point. Provenance is complete and traceable from raw experimental data through simulation outputs to this decision record. The weight of structured evidence supports acceptance of the CFD hemolysis prediction model for the stated COU.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
